"Kulongoski J.T., Hilton D.R., Izbicki J.A., Belitz K.","Evidence for prolonged El Nino-like conditions in the Pacific during the Late Pleistocene: a 43 ka noble gas record from California groundwaters",2009,"Quaternary Science Reviews","28","23-24",,"2465","2473",,,10.1016/j.quascirev.2009.05.008,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70349154118&partnerID=40&md5=0cb7adfff02efc8a4df6674ec50b79d3","U.S. Geological Survey, California Water Science Center, San Diego, CA 92101, United States; Fluids and Volatiles Laboratory, Scripps Institution of Oceanography, UCSD, La Jolla, CA 92093-0244, United States","Kulongoski, J.T., U.S. Geological Survey, California Water Science Center, San Diego, CA 92101, United States, Fluids and Volatiles Laboratory, Scripps Institution of Oceanography, UCSD, La Jolla, CA 92093-0244, United States; Hilton, D.R., Fluids and Volatiles Laboratory, Scripps Institution of Oceanography, UCSD, La Jolla, CA 92093-0244, United States; Izbicki, J.A., U.S. Geological Survey, California Water Science Center, San Diego, CA 92101, United States; Belitz, K., U.S. Geological Survey, California Water Science Center, San Diego, CA 92101, United States","Information on the ocean/atmosphere state over the period spanning the Last Glacial Maximum - from the Late Pleistocene to the Holocene - provides crucial constraints on the relationship between orbital forcing and global climate change. The Pacific Ocean is particularly important in this respect because of its dominant role in exporting heat and moisture from the tropics to higher latitudes. Through targeting groundwaters in the Mojave Desert, California, we show that noble gas derived temperatures in California averaged 4.2 ± 1.1 °C cooler in the Late Pleistocene (from ∼43 to ∼12 ka) compared to the Holocene (from ∼10 to ∼5 ka). Furthermore, the older groundwaters contain higher concentrations of excess air (entrained air bubbles) and have elevated oxygen-18/oxygen-16 ratios (δ 18O) - indicators of vigorous aquifer recharge, and greater rainfall amounts and/or more intense precipitation events, respectively. Together, these paleoclimate indicators reveal that cooler and wetter conditions prevailed in the Mojave Desert from ∼43 to ∼12 ka. We suggest that during the Late Pleistocene, the Pacific ocean/atmosphere state was similar to present-day El Nino-like patterns, and was characterized by prolonged periods of weak trade winds, weak upwelling along the eastern Pacific margin, and increased precipitation in the southwestern U.S.",,"Aquifer recharge; California; Eastern pacific; EL Nino; Entrained air; Excess air; Global climate changes; Higher latitudes; Holocenes; Intense precipitation; Last Glacial Maximum; Late Pleistocene; Mojave Desert; Noble gas; Orbital forcing; Oxygen-18; Pacific ocean; Paleoclimates; Trade winds; Aquifers; Arctic engineering; Cooling systems; Hydrogeology; Inert gases; Landforms; Oceanography; Oxygen; Recharging (underground waters); Climate change; climate change; El Nino; global climate; groundwater; historical record; Holocene; noble gas; paleoclimate; Pleistocene; precipitation intensity; recharge; trade wind; upwelling; California; Mojave Desert; North America; Pacific Ocean; United States",,,,,,"Aeschbach-Hertig, W., Peeters, F., Beyerle, U., Kipfer, R., Interpretation of dissolved atmospheric noble gases in natural waters (1999) Wat. Res. Res., 35, pp. 2779-2792; Aeschbach-Hertig, W., Peeters, F., Beyerle, U., Kipfer, R., Paleotemperature reconstruction from noble gases in ground water taking into account equilibration with entrapped air (2000) Nature, 405, pp. 1040-1044; Aeschbach-Hertig, W., Stute, M., Clark, J.F., Reuter, R.F., Schlosser, P., A paleotemperature record derived from dissolved noble gases in groundwater of the Aquia Aquifer (Maryland, USA) (2002) Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 66, pp. 797-817; Altabet, M.A., Higginson, M.J., Murray, D.W., The effect of millennial-scale changes in Arabian Sea denitrification o